1
00:00:00,260 --> 00:00:03,570
I hope you enjoyed
the videos on how you

2
00:00:03,570 --> 00:00:06,270
can build your own
recommender system.

3
00:00:06,270 --> 00:00:08,610
Before we wrap up
this week in this and

4
00:00:08,610 --> 00:00:11,280
a few other optional videos
I'd like to share with

5
00:00:11,280 --> 00:00:14,220
you an unsupervised
learning algorithm

6
00:00:14,220 --> 00:00:17,055
called principal
components analysis.

7
00:00:17,055 --> 00:00:18,660
This is an algorithm that is

8
00:00:18,660 --> 00:00:21,210
commonly used for visualization.

9
00:00:21,210 --> 00:00:22,710
Specifically, if you

10
00:00:22,710 --> 00:00:24,720
have a dataset with
a lot of features,

11
00:00:24,720 --> 00:00:26,400
say 10 features or

12
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:28,815
50 features or even
thousands of features,

13
00:00:28,815 --> 00:00:32,790
you can't plot 1,000
dimensional data.

14
00:00:32,790 --> 00:00:35,770
PCA, or principal
components analysis

15
00:00:35,770 --> 00:00:36,920
is an algorithm that lets

16
00:00:36,920 --> 00:00:40,575
you take data with a lot
of features, 50, 1,000,

17
00:00:40,575 --> 00:00:42,349
even more, and reduce

18
00:00:42,349 --> 00:00:44,570
the number of features
to two features,

19
00:00:44,570 --> 00:00:46,580
maybe three features,
so that you

20
00:00:46,580 --> 00:00:48,740
can plot it and visualize it.

21
00:00:48,740 --> 00:00:50,420
Is commonly used by

22
00:00:50,420 --> 00:00:52,850
data scientists to
visualize the data,

23
00:00:52,850 --> 00:00:54,485
to figure out what
might be going on.

24
00:00:54,485 --> 00:00:56,585
Let's take a look at how PCA,

25
00:00:56,585 --> 00:00:59,455
principal components
analysis works.

26
00:00:59,455 --> 00:01:03,770
To describe PCA, I'm going
to use as a running example,

27
00:01:03,770 --> 00:01:08,660
if you have data from a
collection of passenger cars,

28
00:01:08,660 --> 00:01:11,795
and passenger cars can
have a lot of features.

29
00:01:11,795 --> 00:01:14,480
You may know the length of

30
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:17,630
the car or the width of the car,

31
00:01:17,630 --> 00:01:20,840
maybe the diameter of the wheel,

32
00:01:20,840 --> 00:01:23,885
or maybe the height of the car,

33
00:01:23,885 --> 00:01:27,395
and many other features of cars.

34
00:01:27,395 --> 00:01:29,540
If you want to reduce

35
00:01:29,540 --> 00:01:32,435
the number of features
so you can visualize it,

36
00:01:32,435 --> 00:01:35,725
how can you use PCA to do so?

37
00:01:35,725 --> 00:01:38,195
For the first example,

38
00:01:38,195 --> 00:01:41,690
let's say you're given a
dataset with two features.

39
00:01:41,690 --> 00:01:45,260
The feature x_1 is the
length of the car,

40
00:01:45,260 --> 00:01:50,300
like so, and the
second feature x_2,

41
00:01:50,300 --> 00:01:52,055
is the width of the car,

42
00:01:52,055 --> 00:01:55,150
which is measured like so.

43
00:01:55,150 --> 00:01:58,610
It turns out that
in most countries,

44
00:01:58,610 --> 00:02:00,830
because of constraints
about the width

45
00:02:00,830 --> 00:02:03,230
of the road the cars drive on,

46
00:02:03,230 --> 00:02:05,375
width of the car
which has got to fit

47
00:02:05,375 --> 00:02:08,195
within the width of the
road of a single lane,

48
00:02:08,195 --> 00:02:10,320
tends not to vary that much.

49
00:02:10,320 --> 00:02:13,085
For example, in
the United States,

50
00:02:13,085 --> 00:02:14,745
most cars are,

51
00:02:14,745 --> 00:02:18,470
let's call it about
1.8 meters wide,

52
00:02:18,470 --> 00:02:20,930
that's just under six feet.

53
00:02:20,930 --> 00:02:23,780
If you were to have
a collection of

54
00:02:23,780 --> 00:02:25,670
cars and the dataset of

55
00:02:25,670 --> 00:02:28,065
the length and
width of the cars,

56
00:02:28,065 --> 00:02:32,405
you will find that the
dataset might look like this,

57
00:02:32,405 --> 00:02:36,140
where x_1 varies quite a bit
because some cars are really

58
00:02:36,140 --> 00:02:41,260
long and x_2 varies
relatively little.

59
00:02:41,260 --> 00:02:45,150
If you want to reduce the
number of features, well,

60
00:02:45,150 --> 00:02:48,245
one thing you could do is
let us take x_1 because

61
00:02:48,245 --> 00:02:51,985
x_2 varies relatively
little from car to car.

62
00:02:51,985 --> 00:02:54,470
It turns out that
PCA is an algorithm

63
00:02:54,470 --> 00:02:57,285
that when applied to
this data set will

64
00:02:57,285 --> 00:03:02,615
more or less automatically
decide to just take x_1,

65
00:03:02,615 --> 00:03:04,685
but it can do much
more than that.

66
00:03:04,685 --> 00:03:07,640
Let's look at a second example

67
00:03:07,640 --> 00:03:11,875
where here x_1 is again
the length of the car,

68
00:03:11,875 --> 00:03:14,835
and let's say that
in this dataset,

69
00:03:14,835 --> 00:03:18,465
x_2 is the diameter
of the wheel.

70
00:03:18,465 --> 00:03:22,185
The diameter of the wheel
does vary a little bit.

71
00:03:22,185 --> 00:03:24,230
If you were to plot the data,

72
00:03:24,230 --> 00:03:25,850
it might look like this.

73
00:03:25,850 --> 00:03:29,060
But again, if you want to

74
00:03:29,060 --> 00:03:32,645
simplify this dataset
to just one feature,

75
00:03:32,645 --> 00:03:35,570
you might decide, let's
just take x_1 and

76
00:03:35,570 --> 00:03:38,865
forget x_2 and PCA when
applied to this dataset.

77
00:03:38,865 --> 00:03:40,955
Well, again, more or less,

78
00:03:40,955 --> 00:03:44,275
cause you to just
check the feature x_1.

79
00:03:44,275 --> 00:03:46,400
In both the examples we saw,

80
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:49,055
only one of the two
features seemed

81
00:03:49,055 --> 00:03:52,840
to have a meaningful
degree of variation.

82
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:55,515
Here's a more complex example.

83
00:03:55,515 --> 00:03:58,760
Say the feature x_1 is
the length of the car,

84
00:03:58,760 --> 00:04:00,460
so that varies quite a bit,

85
00:04:00,460 --> 00:04:04,265
and the feature x_2 here
is the height of the car,

86
00:04:04,265 --> 00:04:06,200
which also varies quite a bit.

87
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:08,750
Some cars are much
taller than other cars.

88
00:04:08,750 --> 00:04:10,775
If you were to plot the data,

89
00:04:10,775 --> 00:04:13,520
you might get a dataset
that looks like this,

90
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:15,680
where some cars are bigger and

91
00:04:15,680 --> 00:04:17,990
they tend to be
longer and taller,

92
00:04:17,990 --> 00:04:20,000
and some cars are a
little bit smaller.

93
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:23,735
They tend to be not as
long and not as tall.

94
00:04:23,735 --> 00:04:26,600
If you wanted to
reduce the number of

95
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:29,285
features, what should you pick?

96
00:04:29,285 --> 00:04:31,500
You don't want to pick
just x_1, the length,

97
00:04:31,500 --> 00:04:33,105
and ignore x_2 the height

98
00:04:33,105 --> 00:04:35,385
and you also don't
want to pick just x_2,

99
00:04:35,385 --> 00:04:38,145
the height, and ignore
x_1, the length.

100
00:04:38,145 --> 00:04:42,660
It seems as if both x_1 and
x_2 have useful information.

101
00:04:42,660 --> 00:04:44,340
In this graph,

102
00:04:44,340 --> 00:04:49,485
x_1 and x_2 are the
two axes of this plot.

103
00:04:49,485 --> 00:04:52,310
Instead of being
limited to taking

104
00:04:52,310 --> 00:04:55,505
either the x_1 axis
or the x_2 axis,

105
00:04:55,505 --> 00:04:58,145
what if we had a third axis.

106
00:04:58,145 --> 00:05:02,250
I'm going to call this
new axis the z-axis.

107
00:05:02,250 --> 00:05:05,435
To be clear, this is not
sticking out of this diagram.

108
00:05:05,435 --> 00:05:08,510
This is a combination
of x_1 and x_2.

109
00:05:08,510 --> 00:05:10,760
This is not a z-axis

110
00:05:10,760 --> 00:05:13,370
that's sticking out in
the third dimension.

111
00:05:13,370 --> 00:05:17,790
This z-axis lies flat
within this plot.

112
00:05:17,790 --> 00:05:20,360
But why do we have
the z-axis which

113
00:05:20,360 --> 00:05:25,035
corresponds to something
about the size of the car?

114
00:05:25,035 --> 00:05:29,015
Given a car like this one
over here, its coordinate,

115
00:05:29,015 --> 00:05:31,550
meaning the value
on the x-axis tells

116
00:05:31,550 --> 00:05:34,775
us the length of the car
and the coordinate is just,

117
00:05:34,775 --> 00:05:36,500
what is this distance?

118
00:05:36,500 --> 00:05:39,650
Similarly its
coordinate, meaning,

119
00:05:39,650 --> 00:05:41,990
what is this distance on

120
00:05:41,990 --> 00:05:46,030
the x_2 axis tells us what
is the height of the car.

121
00:05:46,030 --> 00:05:48,995
If we're now going to
use the z-axis instead

122
00:05:48,995 --> 00:05:52,130
as one feature to capture what

123
00:05:52,130 --> 00:05:55,100
we know about this car
then is coordinate on

124
00:05:55,100 --> 00:05:58,460
the z-axis, meaning
this distance.

125
00:05:58,460 --> 00:06:03,025
That tells us roughly what
is the size of the car.

126
00:06:03,025 --> 00:06:07,100
We'll formalize this in
the next few videos.

127
00:06:07,100 --> 00:06:13,775
But the idea of PCA is to
find one or more new axes,

128
00:06:13,775 --> 00:06:16,370
such as z so that when you

129
00:06:16,370 --> 00:06:20,165
measure your datas
coordinates on the new axis,

130
00:06:20,165 --> 00:06:21,980
you end up still with

131
00:06:21,980 --> 00:06:25,145
very useful information
about the car.

132
00:06:25,145 --> 00:06:28,175
But maybe now,
instead of needing

133
00:06:28,175 --> 00:06:30,140
two numbers corresponding to

134
00:06:30,140 --> 00:06:33,215
the coordinates on
X_1 and X_2 axes,

135
00:06:33,215 --> 00:06:34,910
the length and height.

136
00:06:34,910 --> 00:06:37,505
You now need a few
numbers, in this case,

137
00:06:37,505 --> 00:06:39,785
only one number instead of two,

138
00:06:39,785 --> 00:06:42,860
to capture roughly
the size of the car.

139
00:06:42,860 --> 00:06:45,965
In the example,
we've used so far,

140
00:06:45,965 --> 00:06:49,745
we were trying to reduce
the data from two numbers,

141
00:06:49,745 --> 00:06:52,925
X_1 and X_2 down to one number,

142
00:06:52,925 --> 00:06:55,415
the coordinate on the z-axis.

143
00:06:55,415 --> 00:06:58,280
In practice, PCA
is usually used to

144
00:06:58,280 --> 00:07:01,355
reduce a very large
number of features,

145
00:07:01,355 --> 00:07:02,600
say 10, 20,

146
00:07:02,600 --> 00:07:05,585
50, even thousands of features,

147
00:07:05,585 --> 00:07:10,970
down to maybe two or three
features so that you can

148
00:07:10,970 --> 00:07:12,890
visualize the data in a

149
00:07:12,890 --> 00:07:16,520
two-dimensional or in a
three-dimensional plot.

150
00:07:16,520 --> 00:07:18,380
But for this video,

151
00:07:18,380 --> 00:07:22,520
because I could only draw on
a two-dimensional screen.

152
00:07:22,520 --> 00:07:24,529
I'm going to use mainly

153
00:07:24,529 --> 00:07:27,050
two or three-dimensional
data sets

154
00:07:27,050 --> 00:07:28,850
as my examples.

155
00:07:28,850 --> 00:07:31,415
Let's look at one more example.

156
00:07:31,415 --> 00:07:35,120
In this visualization, we
have a three-dimensional data

157
00:07:35,120 --> 00:07:39,095
set and notice that I can
rotate the data set here,

158
00:07:39,095 --> 00:07:40,955
so you can see it in 3D.

159
00:07:40,955 --> 00:07:45,170
But notice if I rotate
the data set like this,

160
00:07:45,170 --> 00:07:47,135
well, most of this data,

161
00:07:47,135 --> 00:07:48,710
even though it is in 3D,

162
00:07:48,710 --> 00:07:53,225
it actually lives on
a very thin surface.

163
00:07:53,225 --> 00:07:55,400
It's almost as if
all the data lies

164
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:57,755
on a two-dimensional pancake,

165
00:07:57,755 --> 00:07:59,165
even though the pancake

166
00:07:59,165 --> 00:08:01,880
lives in this
three-dimensional space.

167
00:08:01,880 --> 00:08:04,625
A PCA, what you can do is,

168
00:08:04,625 --> 00:08:08,210
instead of having
three features, x_1,

169
00:08:08,210 --> 00:08:10,415
x_2, x_3,

170
00:08:10,415 --> 00:08:12,800
reduce it to two numbers,

171
00:08:12,800 --> 00:08:16,610
which we're going to
call Z_1 and Z_2.

172
00:08:16,610 --> 00:08:18,200
When you do that,

173
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:22,100
you can then visualize
the data on this Z_1,

174
00:08:22,100 --> 00:08:25,010
Z_2 axis and this becomes

175
00:08:25,010 --> 00:08:29,675
a convenient way to visualize
this data if you had to,

176
00:08:29,675 --> 00:08:31,580
say print on a piece of paper.

177
00:08:31,580 --> 00:08:33,230
I couldn't dynamically rotate

178
00:08:33,230 --> 00:08:35,630
it like you'll seeing
me do on the screen.

179
00:08:35,630 --> 00:08:37,355
Here's one more example.

180
00:08:37,355 --> 00:08:39,440
If you have data about

181
00:08:39,440 --> 00:08:42,980
the development status of
many different countries,

182
00:08:42,980 --> 00:08:44,675
you might have for example

183
00:08:44,675 --> 00:08:47,030
data about different countries,

184
00:08:47,030 --> 00:08:50,135
GDP, and that's feature x_1.

185
00:08:50,135 --> 00:08:52,985
In addition, Let's
say we also have

186
00:08:52,985 --> 00:08:56,195
the per capita GDP and also

187
00:08:56,195 --> 00:08:59,750
a measure of their Human
Development Index.

188
00:08:59,750 --> 00:09:03,335
The Human Development
Index was developed

189
00:09:03,335 --> 00:09:07,250
to measure the overall
progress of how well

190
00:09:07,250 --> 00:09:09,290
people in a country might be

191
00:09:09,290 --> 00:09:12,050
doing based on things
like the lifespan and

192
00:09:12,050 --> 00:09:13,760
education and so on

193
00:09:13,760 --> 00:09:16,940
or you might separately
have a feature

194
00:09:16,940 --> 00:09:20,600
corresponding to
the life expectancy

195
00:09:20,600 --> 00:09:23,945
in different countries
and so on and so forth.

196
00:09:23,945 --> 00:09:28,025
If for each country
you have 50 features,

197
00:09:28,025 --> 00:09:31,310
how can you visualize this
data because you can't plot

198
00:09:31,310 --> 00:09:33,215
50 dimensional data on

199
00:09:33,215 --> 00:09:35,840
a two-dimensional
computer monitor.

200
00:09:35,840 --> 00:09:38,180
What PCLS will do is take

201
00:09:38,180 --> 00:09:42,470
these 50 features,
X_1,X_2,X_3,X_4,

202
00:09:42,470 --> 00:09:45,155
and so on and compress it

203
00:09:45,155 --> 00:09:48,155
down to two features
which I'm going to call

204
00:09:48,155 --> 00:09:51,515
Z_1 and Z_2 and you can then

205
00:09:51,515 --> 00:09:56,270
plot these different countries
values of z_1 and z_2.

206
00:09:56,270 --> 00:10:01,070
You might find for example
that Z_1 loosely corresponds

207
00:10:01,070 --> 00:10:05,600
to how big is the country
and what is this total GDP?

208
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:09,035
Because larger countries
tend to have a higher GDP,

209
00:10:09,035 --> 00:10:11,420
because large countries
have many people,

210
00:10:11,420 --> 00:10:14,105
tend to have a larger economy

211
00:10:14,105 --> 00:10:18,140
and perhaps you find that Z_2

212
00:10:18,140 --> 00:10:22,970
corresponds roughly
to the per person GDP

213
00:10:22,970 --> 00:10:26,420
or the amount of economic
activity per person.

214
00:10:26,420 --> 00:10:29,595
For example, the United States,

215
00:10:29,595 --> 00:10:32,860
which is a relatively
large country and has

216
00:10:32,860 --> 00:10:36,205
relatively high per
person economic activity

217
00:10:36,205 --> 00:10:39,370
may be somewhere up here
to the up and right of

218
00:10:39,370 --> 00:10:43,010
this plot and a country
like Singapore,

219
00:10:43,010 --> 00:10:44,825
where I live many years as well,

220
00:10:44,825 --> 00:10:47,210
is a smaller country but it has

221
00:10:47,210 --> 00:10:50,630
relatively high per
person economic activity.

222
00:10:50,630 --> 00:10:54,620
Take on a lower value
on the z_1 axis,

223
00:10:54,620 --> 00:10:58,130
but still a relatively high
value on the z_2 axis.

224
00:10:58,130 --> 00:11:01,160
Whereas a country like
this would be maybe

225
00:11:01,160 --> 00:11:02,540
a smaller country with

226
00:11:02,540 --> 00:11:04,910
lower per person
economic activity.

227
00:11:04,910 --> 00:11:08,510
Whereas the country like this
may be a large country with

228
00:11:08,510 --> 00:11:11,870
lower per person economic
activity and a figure like

229
00:11:11,870 --> 00:11:13,115
this lets you take

230
00:11:13,115 --> 00:11:15,815
a large number of
features, 50 features.

231
00:11:15,815 --> 00:11:18,875
Sometimes we also say
that's 50 dimensional data.

232
00:11:18,875 --> 00:11:21,290
It just means we
have 50 features and

233
00:11:21,290 --> 00:11:24,530
reduce that to two features
or sometimes we say

234
00:11:24,530 --> 00:11:27,380
is two-dimensional data because
you can then plot it on

235
00:11:27,380 --> 00:11:30,705
this two-dimensional plot
like you're seeing here.

236
00:11:30,705 --> 00:11:32,635
Whenever I get a new data set,

237
00:11:32,635 --> 00:11:35,769
one of the things I'll often
want to do is to visualize

238
00:11:35,769 --> 00:11:37,270
the data since that helps me

239
00:11:37,270 --> 00:11:39,280
understand what the
data looks like,

240
00:11:39,280 --> 00:11:40,900
what do the countries look like,

241
00:11:40,900 --> 00:11:43,720
or what do the cars seem
like in this data set

242
00:11:43,720 --> 00:11:47,025
or whatever data you
may be examining.

243
00:11:47,025 --> 00:11:50,210
You find also that
visualizing the data set will

244
00:11:50,210 --> 00:11:51,845
sometimes help you figure out

245
00:11:51,845 --> 00:11:54,035
something funny's going
on in this datas.

246
00:11:54,035 --> 00:11:56,210
Something unexpected
is happening.

247
00:11:56,210 --> 00:11:58,700
PCA is a powerful algorithm

248
00:11:58,700 --> 00:12:01,115
for taking data with
a lot of features,

249
00:12:01,115 --> 00:12:03,935
with a lot of dimensions
or high-dimensional data,

250
00:12:03,935 --> 00:12:07,460
and reducing it to two
or three features to

251
00:12:07,460 --> 00:12:10,490
two or three dimensional
data so you can plot

252
00:12:10,490 --> 00:12:12,020
it and visualize it and better

253
00:12:12,020 --> 00:12:14,630
understand what's in your data.

254
00:12:14,630 --> 00:12:17,620
That's what the PCA
algorithm can do for you.

255
00:12:17,620 --> 00:12:18,830
